v1.953

        - as promised, this release no longer works on v5.8; in fact, due to
          some upstream libraries, it hasn't in some time
        - documentation has been cleaned up to stop referencing long-dead other
          libraries or methods
        - some small code changes to benefit from v5.10 and v5.12 improvements
update Changelog for next release

tests: drop use of Symbol::gensym

we are no longer on a jurassic perl

drop weird documentation about body_set

Yeah, a method in a subclass overrides the one in the base class.
stop even loading Email::MIME::Modifier

stop talking about the long-dead Modifiers package

also, relatedly, stop planning or no-planning

just done_testing at the end
GitHub Actions: add multiperl-test workflow
go ahead and rely on v5.12; upstream already requires it
dist.ini: update author email

v1.952

        - exactly 1.951, except will install on 5.8.8
        - **ACHTUNG!**  Do not expect any future release to work on Perl v5.8
one final 5.8.8 release

v1.951

        - non-trial release of 1.950 changes
AddressList: some pod cleanup
prep next release

v1.950

        - when computing filename, start from raw  Content-Disposition (thanks,
          Mishrakk)
        - avoid a potentially very slow regex in parsing (thanks, ivulfson)
update changelog for next release
fix slow regex to improve performance on parsing large mimeparts (#75)

Update MIME.pm

If we are parsing content disposition, we should probably operate on raw value of header, not already parsed.
This fixes problems with attachments names containing non-ASCII characters

v1.949

        - no changes since trial release
update changelog

v1.948

        - fixes to handling of content-type parameters (thanks, dlucredativ and
          Pali Rohár)
Fix issue 61
Add tests for filename from #18

Use functions build_content_disposition and build_content_type from Email::MIME::ContentType

New version of Email::MIME::ContentType would have functions for composing
Content-Type and Content-Disposition headers.

As a bonus they support Unicode strings encoded to UTF-8 according to
RFC 2231. Therefore Email::MIME can set Unicode file name for the
attachment.

Some tests were slightly modified as attributes do not have to be always
quoted and Email::MIME::ContentType do it only if needed.

Fixes #18
Fixes #31
Do not set undefined Content-Type attribute charset

v1.947

        - add $Email::MIME::MAX_DEPTH and refuse to parse deeper than that many
          parts; current default: 10
prep next trial release
Fix snowman test, parts must contain 8bit data, not Unicode

Fix Email::MIME::Encode::maybe_mime_encode_header to work also without explicit "use Email::MIME::Header"

Email::MIME::Encode uses %Email::MIME::Header::header_to_class_map variable
but have not loaded Email::MIME::Header module. This patch fixes it.

Problem discovered by atoomic in report #52.

Sort hash keys to keep attributes consistent

Hashes in Perl are unsorted, and this can lead to inconsistent ordering. It may be even better to use an array instead of hash map to keep the order, but this is a simple solution for now.
